CI/CD from Kitchen #1: The “CD” part with ArgoCD

Hello and welcome to the first article in the “CI/CD from Kitchen” series.
In the first article, I’m sharing with you my concept of a multi-tenant CI/CD system as a part of an Internal Developer Platform.

I cannot guarantee that it is the best approach in your case, but I hope to inspire you so that you can take useful pieces from it and make your own system. Unfortunately, the creation of a CI/CD Platform strictly depends on individual needs and preferences, therefore I’m describing there only a few concepts, but easily extendable to your needs.

The first part is an example focused on cluster-shaping and application deployment. Next articles in this series will be more focused on the CI.

Let’s start with the recipe!

What’s below?

First I show you how we can build a ground for the CI/CD processes to grow up — we will create an ArgoCD “starter” and then shape up the cluster in an automated way at a scale.

In the process of shaping, you will see how to create a CI/CD system template and propagate it to dozens of teams by simply creating two YAML files.

Additionally, the solution presented there supports as many clusters and teams as you need.

Assumptions:
- We are running on multiple Kubernetes clusters
- CI/CD should be cloud-native and highly available (HA)
- Teams should be separated from each other
- The team is installing or at least configuring Pipelines on their own (extendability)
- Platform Engineering team is responsible for preparing “golden paths” in the form of ready-to-use CI/CD pipelines and for the working platform on top of Kubernetes managed by an infrastructural team
- Pipelines part of the Platform is versioned (in Tekton variant at least)

Example architecture

Legend:

  1. cluster-root: Central repository for managing all clusters and defining all teams cooperating together

2. pipelines-base: Base repository for all CI-related things — from Python/Go Tekton scripts to golden Helm Charts and Pipeline skeletons. Versioned together as a single CI/CD pipelines release. Its a shared repository between teams. Let’s say it out loud — it’s a mono-repository. By the way, check out my article about how to trigger Tekton Pipelines only for components that were changed in a mono-repository

Tekton vs Monolithic repository. How to trigger a pipeline when given directory changes?

Monolithic repositories are often recognized with legacy or modular development projects, in my case I used a…

3. release-repository: A repository, where the team has its infrastructural files placed. There is a CI/CD pipelines definition as well as information about which version of which application should go on which environment. Every team has its own release repository

Getting familiar with ArgoCD

In case you are not familiar yet with ArgoCD, I recommend you to read a getting started guide for an easier understanding of the whole article.

Argo CD — an Introduction

Introduction to Argo CD — Part 1

faun.pub

At the beginning — creating a “CD” installer

Every cluster being a part of your developer platform ecosystem needs to be configured somehow. Placing the configuration in a common repository makes it clear how to bootstrap everything, that’s a “starting point”.

Create a “cluster-root” repository, and a “bootstrap” or “starter” directory.
There you can write simple bash scripts + Kustomize overlays or create Terraform automation with multiple input files depending on the cluster you want to provision.

I will go with the maybe not best, but simplest solution there, just for an example — let’s create a directory per cluster and a simple bash script:

Example logic:

  1. Install ArgoCD Operator
  2. Install SealedSecrets controller
  3. Create a kind: ArgoCD object to create a new, cluster-scoped ArgoCD instance that will manage CI/CD stacks in our ecosystem

On this level, you should configure SSO and bind OIDC groups to ArgoCD permissions, configure Ingress or OpenShift’s Route.

Congratulations, you have a basic cluster-scoped ArgoCD instance installed! Now let’s shape the cluster with it.

Shaping the cluster

Check the below example structure, and description under it.

  1. bootstrap — there you have your bootstrap scripts installing ArgoCD Operator and ArgoCD cluster-scoped instance
  2. src — infrastructural YAMLs and Helm Chart sources you may want to keep in the same repository for consistency and a big picture of the system
  3. clusters — on/off switches per cluster to turn on selected automation like “production namespaces preparation” on production-type clusters, “continuous integration stacks creation” on CI-type clusters. There also you enable synchronization of selected paths from “src” or from external Helm Charts to e.g. install Grafana or other software. Your AppOfApps tile should point there
  4. teams — CI/CD stacks definitions per cluster per team

On/Off switches per cluster (cluster/ directory)

Let’s first start with this concept, all below automation examples are controlled in this way.

In clusters/ directory you have a bases subdirectory where your ArgoCD’s kind: Application and kind: ApplicationSet lays without specific information tied to the cluster.

Example of a clusters/bases/cicd-stacks base automation directory:

Example of a patch for a specific cluster in clusters/preprod/cicd-stacks.patch.yaml:

Please notice the following:

  • The “base” file contains placeholders, that should be parametrized by a patch
  • A patch is defined per cluster to adjust the automation to that specific cluster. It may be a different file pattern in GIT generator, a different namespace, other naming patterns, or specific branch pointing to YAML resources for example
  • You are turning on/off whole directories (bases) with multiple automation, not files (that's how Kustomize works)
  • You can “cd” into a subdirectory containing patches and do “kustomize build” to render and verify locally

“production-systems-configuration”

(On production-type cluster)

Use ApplicationSet to iterate through all files matching the pattern /teams/*/prod-cluster.yaml , in result creating tiles named like team-1-prod-config to bootstrap all basic things that the team needs in the “production cluster”. Those objects can include for example Namespaces, ServiceAccounts, RoleBindings, NetworkPolicies, LimitRanges, and ResourceQuotas.

Hints:

  • Disable pruning for namespaces using at least Prune=false annotation
  • Disable automatic deletion of kind: Application when prod-cluster.yaml disappears from the repository (preserveResourcesOnDeletion in ApplicationSet)
  • You can additionally use a post-sync hook to write the generated ServiceAccount token into the CI-cluster or somewhere else to fully automate this process.

Results:

  • Automatic creation of namespaces in a safe way (typo in repo or file deletion does not automatically remove namespace, you have to remove it manually)
  • Automatically created ServiceAccount let’s your CI process or better, different ArgoCD installed per team to reach the production namespace for deployment in a strictly controlled way (you limit the permissions using RBAC on the ServiceAccount)

“operational”

(On every cluster)

In case you need a centralized way to manage the security or resource planning, then you may create a separate automation for it. Use ApplicationSet to manage objects like LimitRanges, NetworkPolicies and RoleBindings per namespace.

Simply — enable automation on each cluster, and on each cluster iterate over /operational/{clusterName}/* directory using ApplicationSet’s GIT Directory generator.

In effect for each directory that would create an ArgoCD’s kind: Application synchronizing that directory — there you can use plain YAMLs or Kustomize easily and independently for each directory.

Create a simple README.md and grant development teams access to create Pull Requests, so they can apply for network traffic whitelisting or increasing the memory limits. You have a full overview of everything.

“persistent-storage”

(On every cluster)

Managing Persistent Volumes requires being extra careful, it’s our user's data that we do not want to lose. On the other hand, it is good to have an overview of where the resources are assigned to. Therefore it's good to have separate automation for it to sleep safely. My recommendation is to not deploy PV & PVC's together with the application.

A simple, flat directory with well-named YAML files containing one PersistentVolume per file could be enough.

Hints:

  • Do not store multiple objects in a single YAML file, it’s very important! (to avoid mistakes like one document overwrites another when you miss the separator)
  • Disable pruning via annotation as well as in kind: Application automated synchronization options (prune: false) if using automated
  • Disable resources overlapping (FailOnSharedResource=true)
  • Disable kind: Application deletion in ApplicationSet if you decide to use hierarchical structure and ApplicationSet

“cicd-stacks”

(On CI-type clusters)

That’s the bigger topic actually. To achieve a full multi-tenancy I suggest deploying an ArgoCD instance for each team in their dedicated namespace.

To prepare freshly deployed ArgoCD instance, in a team’s namespace we can inject for example:

  • A production token secret in a proper format allowing to access that team’s production namespace only
  • A mix of kind: AppProject and kind: Application objects to make sure that apps will be synchronized from specified directories in release repositories owned by teams. In simple words — pin directories containing application releases into synchronization. A release means committing a file by a CI Pipeline to the release repository after passed automated tests
  • Service Monitors for Prometheus to collect metrics from Pipelines
  • RBAC
  • Post-synchronization jobs to create access in artifactory, propagate credentials to team’s namespaces, to pin Gitlab/Github/Gitea webhooks — everything that cannot be done with ready-to-use tools and should be programmed in Python, Bash, or Go for example
  • Crossplane or Terraform post-sync tasks to create Gitlab/Github/Gitea repository

Effect:

  • CI/CD stack out-of-the-box
  • Easy project/team onboarding by just creating a YAML file in the repository
  • A strong separation between teams
  • Predefined settings of created ArgoCD instances make those instances ready to be used

I will cover more details in the second article about this concept, it is so big that a dedicated part will be created. Especially the part about customizations and teams' self-service.

ArgoCD and CI system per team

In order to achieve solid-rock isolation and autonomy between multiple teams I suggest creating separated instances of both CI (like Jenkins or Tekton) and CD.

This approach has a few advantages:

  • One instance does not break another (there are cases like higher memory usage by Kustomize that could happen)
  • Leverage Kubernetes-native tools like RBAC, NetworkPolicies, ResourceQuotas, UID randomization, Separate Node Pools per tenant, AppArmor/SELinux, KubeArmor, and other
  • By having multiple ArgoCD for each cluster we don’t need to have allowed a network connection and credentials between clusters

Hints:

  • The cluster-level instance should have cluster-admin access to the whole cluster (use ARGOCD_CLUSTER_CONFIG_NAMESPACES environment variable in operator settings to point in which namespace there should be a cluster-scoped instance installed)
  • The team-level instance should have access only limited to reach its own namespace and other team namespaces. Create team namespaces from cluster-level ArgoCD instance and label them with argocd.argoproj.io/managed-by: {instance-name-here} , so the ArgoCD operator will grant permissions for your team-level ArgoCD instances to labeled namespaces
  • You can use custom roles for team-level instances to forbid messing with ResourceQuotas, NetworkPolicies, and other things that apply restrictions on a team namespace

Finally, the “CD” part — deploying applications from team-level ArgoCD

As a part of installing the ArgoCD team-level per every team we have the possibility to pre-configure all of those instances — why not?

We can inject not only credentials allowing access to the release repository, but also we can make the release repository synchronized.

This can be done in at least two ways:

  • To create kind: AppProject + kind: Application together with the ArgoCD instance (apply to the cluster all at once). The whole cicd-stack could be a local Helm Chart representing a cicd that consists of pre-configured ArgoCD together with some CI system and maybe pipelines
  • To automatically create a GIT repository from a template, where kind: AppProject and kind: Application would be already there

So! Assuming our team-level ArgoCD has a release repository synchronization, whenever the CI pipeline finishes we end up in a YAML committed to the GIT repository, and then deployed by the team-level ArgoCD.

Yay! We made all of this to easily onboard every team, and every project out of the box, from a template on a scale. Now we only need a CI part.

Summary

The described approach lets you define an almost fully automated system with the following features:

  • Create a pair of “ci-cluster.yaml” and “prod-cluster.yaml” to onboard a new team. Details of it I will describe more in the second article of this series
  • Have a common repository, decide which automation is working on which cluster
  • Manage security and storage in a centralized way
  • It’s a very scalable solution, easily extendible to support e.g. virtual clusters

Read more about “golden paths” from a fantastic article published on the RedHat website.
